## C. KnightWerx fork — deviations from upstream

Commits affecting these loops, found in `git log` on this branch:

### 1. Attitude D-term (commit `76328d9640`, Henry Won, 2024-09-10)

The single substantive controller change vs upstream PX4 in this area. Files modified:
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/AttitudeControl/AttitudeControl.{cpp,hpp}` — `update()` now takes `rates` and applies `-rates.emult(_derivative_gain)`.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control.hpp` — added `_derivative_gain` member, `setDerivativeGain()`.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_main.cpp` — passes `rates` to `update()` (line 303), loads three new params on parameter update.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_params.c` — defines `MC_ROLL_D`, `MC_PITCH_D`, `MC_YAW_D` (all default 0.0).

Effective controller is now **P+D on attitude**, with the inner rate loop unchanged. The hard-coded member init at `AttitudeControl.hpp:106` is `{0.1f, 0.f, 0.f}` (roll-only damping) but the params overwrite that on boot, so the runtime default is `{0,0,0}` unless you set the params.

**Implication for SysID and tuning**: with default params (all D=0), this fork is mathematically identical to upstream. If you set any `MC_*_D > 0`, you're adding rate-proportional damping to the *attitude* loop, which couples back through the rate setpoint sent to the inner loop — the inner-loop FRF is unaffected, but the outer-loop and cascade FRFs will shift.

### 2. Heading-good-for-control reset bypass (in same commit and surroundings, `mc_att_control_main.cpp:331`)

A comment in the file reads "bypassing this check as it has been overactively setting false" — the `heading_good_for_control` reset path that would have re-baselined the yaw setpoint during autonomous flight is disabled. Behavioral effect: yaw setpoints don't get reset under EKF heading-quality drops. Worth knowing if you see unexpected yaw drift in flight logs.

### 3. Rate controller — no fork divergence

`git log hotfix..origin/dev -- src/modules/mc_rate_control/ src/lib/rate_control/` returns nothing. The rate loop in this repo is byte-identical to the dev branch on the same files. The commented-out anti-windup gate (`rate_control.cpp:92-99`) is also upstream behavior, not a local change.

